#: ../../white-paper/metadata-schema-recommendations.rst:217
msgid ""
"Why RRIDs? RRIDs are currently used in about 1000 journals to tag classes of"
" research resources (including reagents like antibodies or plasmids, "
"organisms, cell lines, and a relatively broad category of “tools” which "
"includes software tools and services such as university core facilities, but"
" recently has been extended to physical tools such as models of sequencers "
"or microscopes). Because RRIDs were created as an agreement between a group "
"of biological journals and the National Institutes of Health, they are most "
"commonly found and linked in the biological sciences literature (e.g., Cell,"
" eLife), they are part of the JATS NISO standard, STAR Methods, and the MDAR"
" pan-publisher reproducibility checklist, resolved by identifiers.org and "
"the n2t resolver and echoed by some of the major reagent providers (e.g., "
"Thermo Fisher, Addgene, and the MMRRC mouse repository)."
